# Testing

Implements: ADR-013. WHY: `docs/architecture/adr-013-testing-strategy.md`.

## Agent rule

Do **not** execute `php artisan test`, `composer test`, `npm test`, or CI test commands unless the user explicitly asks. After changes, **state** the suggested filter/path for the user to run.

(This is also restated in `architecture.mdc` so it applies outside `tests/`.)

## Pyramid

| Type | Path | Use for |
| :--- | :--- | :--- |
| **Unit** | `tests/Unit/` | Pure logic isolable from DB/framework. If it needs `RefreshDatabase`/RBAC seeds, it is a Feature test. |
| **Feature** | `tests/Feature/` | **Primary** coverage — Service business rules, HTTP contracts, RBAC boundaries |
| **Integration** | `tests/Integration/` | Cross-module flows via events/services (e.g. loyalty cart→sale→points) |
| **Browser** | (not standard yet) | Add deliberately for high-value journeys only (Dusk/Playwright) — not blanket E2E |
| **Performance** | targeted | Known risky paths only (invoice sequence locks, bulk import, N+1 hotspots) — ADR-014 |
| **Security** | Feature-shaped | Negative tests: Policy denial, token ability bounds, webhook signature failure, (post-Phase-28) tenant isolation |

## Writing tests

- Every Service business rule gets Feature coverage of **boundary conditions**, not only the happy path
- Shared setup → `tests/Concerns/` traits (`SeedsRbac`, …) — do not copy-paste seed blocks
- Bug fix → regression test that fails before / passes after
- Do not add tests unless the user asks (repo workflow) — when asked, follow this ADR

## Coverage expectations

- No gameable “percentage only” mindset before Phase 16 CI gates
- Rule-based bar: each business rule has boundary tests; financial/audit workflows keep existing suite green
- Phase 16 may add a Services/Repositories/DTOs line-coverage floor — that is a backstop, not a substitute for rule tests

## Commands (for the user)

```bash
composer test
php artisan test --filter=TestName
php artisan test tests/Feature/SomeDomain
./vendor/bin/pint
```
